// Max number of candidates
#define MAX 9

Notice that plurality.c then uses this constant to define a global array‚Äîthat is, an array that any function can access.
// Array of candidates
candidate candidates[MAX];

But what, in this case, is a candidate? In plurality.c, a candidate is a struct. Each candidate has two fields: a string called name representing the candidate‚Äôs name, and an int called votes representing the number of votes the candidate has.
// Candidates have name and vote count
typedef struct
{
    string name;
    int votes;
}
candidate;

